<HEADLINE>
<P>
IACOCCA ON THE INFLUENCE OF FOREIGN LOBBIES IN WASHINGTON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Iacocca neatly sidestepped a couple of subjects in his column. He offers no 
explanation of why truck tariffs are 10 times greater than car tariffs. 
Obviously, there would be no incentive to avoid this excessive (25%) tariff if 
it was anywhere near the level imposed on cars (2.5%). 
</P>
<P>
He also claims we don't send people to foreign countries to influence their 
governments. We just send clandestine CIA operatives to foment uprisings, 
influence elections, and incite assassinations. That's real meddling! Compared 
to that, foreign lobbyists are benign. 
</P>
<P>
JAMES R. CLARK JR. 
</P>
<P>
Torrance 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA022589-0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 23071 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
February 25, 1989, Saturday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part 2; Page 9; Column 1; Letters Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
188 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
IACOCCA ON THE INFLUENCE OF FOREIGN LOBBIES IN WASHINGTON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"From Toshiba to Trucks, We're Being Run Over by Foreign Lobbies," screams the 
headline on Lee Iacocca's column (Op-Ed Page, Feb. 15). Iacocca complains that 
"every time foreign lobbyists in Washington jerk a string . . . the American 
government jumps." Iacocca contends that his complaint is not a tariff issue or 
a trade issue, but "who's got the power to change the" law of the United States 
if they don't happen to like it." 
</P>
<P>
Iacocca argues that the people we elect to make our laws, instead of being 
bought by foreign lobbies, should be bought by American lobbies -- that 
American interests should jerk the strings that make government jump. To this I 
say "the pox on Iacocca and his special-interest groups!" 
</P>
<P>
What we need instead is a separation of state and economy. Let there be no laws 
in the United States that interfere with free market exchanges between willing 
buyers and willing sellers -- regardless of race, sex or nationality. Without 
such laws there will be nothing to sell to lobbyists. Corruption in Washington 
will be vastly diminished. Our welfare will be vastly improved. 
</P>
<P>
ERNST F. GHERMANN 
</P>
<P>
Winnetka 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA022589-0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 23072 </DOCID>
