<HEADLINE>
<P>
WITH RAVELING, USC BASKETBALL PROGRAM CONTINUES TO UNRAVEL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I like George Raveling. Always have. I admired his incredible success in that 
remote outpost, Washington State. 
</P>
<P>
But when Raveling charges that criticisms of his USC program are racially 
motivated, well, it shows that George is losing more than just ballgames. 
</P>
<P>
Within weeks of Raveling's arrival at USC, he forced three blue-chip players, 
two of whom are black, out of USC's basketball program. During his tenure, USC 
is 25-57, has finished in the cellar for two consecutive years, lost 13 
consecutive games this season and is a lock for finishing in the basement for 
the third year in a row. Bob Boyd, coaching year after year against John 
Wooden, was 216-131 at USC. 
</P>
<P>
One more thing. Despite John Thompson's Olympic setback, he has proved year in 
and year out that he can recruit and coach. But if Walt Hazzard is Raveling's 
idea of a great coach, he soon may join him on the sideline. 
</P>
<P>
TOM LALLAS 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
