<HEADLINE>
<P>
IT'S NOT SO 'BAD' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
If Michael Jackson is truly disenchanted because "Bad" did not outsell 
"Thriller," he should look at his unrealistic expectations rather than at Frank 
Dileo ("Pop Star Jackson Fires His Manager," by Patrick Goldstein, Feb. 15). 
</P>
<P>
He might also look at quality. Although "Bad" is a solid album, one of the best 
of the last few years, it certainly is no "Thriller." One listen to "Billie 
Jean" or "Beat It" should remind him of that. 
</P>
<P>
If Jackson were to talk with Prince, Fleetwood Mac, or Peter Frampton, he would 
be overjoyed with "Bad's" sales and ability to stand on its own. After all it 
could have gone the way of the follow-ups to their mega-selling albums. Does 
anybody remember "I'm in You?" 
</P>
<P>
DANA F. WOLF 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
