<HEADLINE>
<P>
POLAND RIOT POLICE BREAK UP PROTEST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WARSAW 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Riot police backed by water cannon, batons and tear gas grenades broke up a 
demonstration Friday by thousands of students protesting police brutality in 
the southern city of Krakow, witnesses said. 
</P>
<P>
One student source said at least two people were hit with concussion grenades 
and hospitalized and about 10 were detained. 
</P>
<P>
Student activist Jacek Plaza said about 4,000 people, most of them students, 
gathered in the market square of Krakow for a march to municipal headquarters 
with a petition demanding the punishment of police for beating demonstrators 
Feb. 17. 
</P>
<P>
"Police barred the way and dispersed the crowd with water cannon, tear gas 
grenades and batons," he said. Other witnesses said the demonstrators had 
hurled stones at the police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
