</TABLECELL>
<CELLRULE>  </CELLRULE>
</TABLEROW>
<ROWRULE>  </ROWRULE>
</TABLE>
<P>
</P>
<P>
As of the end of September, a total of 50 homes in Newport Beach and Santa Ana 
Heights are in a noise-impacted area. The state has several remedies for 
property owners in the area: the homes can be insulated, they can be purchased 
by the county, or the sites can be rezoned for "other non-noise sensitive 
uses," 
</P>
<P>
according to Lynn Dosheery, a county planner who serves as the Santa Ana 
Heights project manager. For instance, the zoning in the area along Acacia and 
Birch streets in Santa Ana Heights has been changed from a general agricultural 
use to a business park, she said. 
</P>
<P>
* Most recent data available 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
TELEPHONE COMPLAINT CALLS 
</P>
<P>
July-September, 1988 
</P>
<P>
The airport's Noise Abatement Office logs noise complaints from local citizens. 
During the third quarter of 1988, the office received a total of 1,322 noise 
complaints from local citizens, a 103% increase from the number of complaints 
received the previous quarter. The increase can be traced to the fact that in 
the summer months, "windows are open, people are outside, and are just 
generally more sensitive to noise," said airport spokeswoman Kathie Rutherford. 
</P>
<P>
Also, Balboa residents had been publicly promoting noise complaints as a part 
of their unsuccessful effort to have jet liners rerouted so that departures 
occur as much over Tustin as they do over Newport Beach. 
</P>
<P>
Flights generally depart southbound over Upper Newport Bay, except when air 
traffic controllers reverse the pattern due to wind conditions. According to 
Assistant Airport Manager Jan Mittermeier, there was no significant change in 
the number of departures over Newport Beach. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
